It seems that nowadays the TensorFlow Model.evaluate returns both the loss and the accuracy in a list so at around 2:05 of the video the comparison val_loss < least_val_loss is no longer working. Maybe they changed what the method returns since this video was published. I got this fixed by referring to the first element of the List (according to the docs the first item is loss and second accuracy) like this:

if val_loss[0] < least_val_loss:
    least_val_loss = val_loss[0]

1:54:01 if you got error : TypeError: unsupported operand type(s) for -: 'float' and 'Value' . Try to add  
  def __rsub__(self,other):
    return other + (-self)
to Value class

@mrdbourke at 1:46:03 
I understood the point behind shuffling due to the experiments but one thing i realized was that ... with the global seed, you were not actually shuffling, it was basically just returning the original unshuffled tensor.
And if i understood correctly, this is not what we intend to achieve if the goal was to not inherit the order of the data.

